### 4. [PLSEO_Schema](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-schema.php#8-227) — `$graph` is instance state but class is a singleton instantiated once per request
**File:** [includes/class-plseo-schema.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-schema.php) · lines 11, 82

The `$graph` array is populated in [output_schema()](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-schema.php#33-94) (called from `wp_head`), and `array_filter` removes falsy entries. This means a `null` logo or empty `sameAs` array on the Organization node can leave those keys in, because `array_filter` only works on the top level. NULL logo and empty array will remain in the JSON-LD output:

```json
"logo": null,
"sameAs": []
```

Fix by removing nulls recursively or filtering before assignment:

```php
$this->graph['organization'] = array_filter([
    ...
    'logo'   => $logo ? [...] : null,
    'sameAs' => array_filter([...]),
]);
```

---

### 5. [PLSEO_OpenGraph](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-opengraph.php#4-109) — `article:published_time` / `article:modified_time` always output for *all* singulars
**File:** [includes/class-plseo-opengraph.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-opengraph.php) · line 82–83

```php
$tags['article:published_time'] = get_post_time( 'c', true, $post_id );
$tags['article:modified_time']  = get_post_modified_time( 'c', true, $post_id );
```

These are output even when `og:type` is [website](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-schema.php#119-128) (pages, CPTs). Article meta properties are only valid when `og:type = article`. Guard them:

```php
if ( is_singular( 'post' ) ) {
    $tags['article:published_time'] = get_post_time( 'c', true, $post_id );
    $tags['article:modified_time']  = get_post_modified_time( 'c', true, $post_id );
}
```

---

### 6. `PLSEO_Helpers::get_post_seo_meta()` — Fallback may return wrong-language meta
**File:** [includes/class-plseo-helpers.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-helpers.php) · line 55–70

When a translated post has no SEO meta, the helper falls back to the **default language** post's meta. This is intentional per the comment, but it can cause the wrong language title/description to appear in `<head>` if a user clears the field on a translation without setting new values. Consider making this opt-in or at least documenting it clearly with a filter:

```php
$value = apply_filters( 'plseo_post_seo_meta_fallback', $value, $post_id, $key, $default_id );
```

---

### 7. `PLSEO_Breadcrumbs::add_breadcrumb_to_graph()` — `get_permalink()` with no argument
**File:** [includes/class-plseo-schema.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/includes/class-plseo-schema.php) · line 215

```php
'@id' => get_permalink() . '#breadcrumb',
```

`get_permalink()` without an argument depends on the current post being in The Loop. This is called from `wp_head` (outside the loop on archive/home pages), which will return `false` and produce `#breadcrumb` as the ID. Use the canonical URL instead:

```php
'@id' => PLSEO_Canonical::get_instance()->get_canonical_url() . '#breadcrumb',
```

---

## 🟡 Security Notes

### 8. [save_fields](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/admin/class-plseo-taxonomy-meta.php#127-141) — Missing `wp_unslash()` on term meta
**File:** [admin/class-plseo-taxonomy-meta.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/admin/class-plseo-taxonomy-meta.php) · lines 133–139

```php
update_term_meta( $term_id, '_plseo_meta_title', sanitize_text_field( $_POST['_plseo_meta_title'] ) );
```

`$_POST` values should be unslashed before sanitizing:

```php
update_term_meta( $term_id, '_plseo_meta_title',
    sanitize_text_field( wp_unslash( $_POST['_plseo_meta_title'] ) )
);
```

---

### 9. [render_tools_page](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/admin/class-plseo-admin.php#126-159) — Missing wrapping div close
**File:** [admin/class-plseo-admin.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/admin/class-plseo-admin.php) · line 156

There is a stray `</div>` on line 156 that closes a `<div>` that was never opened in [render_tools_page](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/admin/class-plseo-admin.php#126-159). This likely relies on [header.php](file:///c:/Users/Administrator/Local%20Sites/demo/app/public/wp-content/plugins/wt-multi-seo-pro/header.php) opening a container that it shouldn't have to.

